title: For Sale:  Rare Mosin Nagant M91/59 Carbine! NOT an M38 or M44 Carbine!
postcontent:
Mosin Nagant Model 1891/59 carbine  $200

This is a relatively rare rifle made in Soviet arsenals after WW2 by shortening a standard M 1891 long rifle. Very few of these are on the market today.

Unlike the M44 carbine this rifle DOES NOT have the cruciform bayonet.  

The rifling also extends all the way to the end of the barrel and IS NOT counter bored like the M44 carbine.

Numbers match. Made from a 1942 dated M91.

This rifle has a decent bore, but does show use. Good wood. Excellent condition overall.

I've shot about 40 rounds through it and it's a great little shooter.

PRIVATE PARTY.

CASH SALES ONLY!

title: For Sale:  DEALERS are you kidding me
postcontent: Come on now.. I see this sight as a useful tool for a private gun owner to sell his firearm without the need to consign to an ffl dealer, but now all i see are ffl dealers taking advantage of this sight. Your a business so create your own website and sell your product that way. You post these lower prices then when you get a bite you charge taxes and a background check fee. It's BS. At the very least purchase some advertisement from arms list and advertise on this website, instead of expecting everything free. Most FFL dealers get direct shipment from the manufacturer at wholesale prices then take the hot or hard to find firearms and instead of selling in store at msrp prices post them on gunbroker for auction and get double if not triple what they pay for a firearm we can not find. Is that honest business?? At least on here a private seller is free to ask whatever but shouldn't a business be held to a standard. That's my thought. I see a pawn shop on here who gives less than half for a gun and then ask retail. Live Free or DIE ....Don't Tread On ME

Capt. Millett, Company E, distinguished himself by conspicuous gallantry and intrepidity above and beyond the call of duty in action. While personally leading his company in an attack against a strongly held position he noted that the 1st Platoon was pinned down by small-arms, automatic, and antitank fire. Capt. Millett ordered the 3d Platoon forward, placed himself at the head of the 2 platoons, and, with fixed bayonet, led the assault up the fire-swept hill. In the fierce charge Capt. Millett bayoneted 2 enemy soldiers and boldly continued on, throwing grenades, clubbing and bayoneting the enemy, while urging his men forward by shouting encouragement. Despite vicious opposing fire, the whirlwind hand-to-hand assault carried to the crest of the hill. His dauntless leadership and personal courage so inspired his men that they stormed into the hostile position and used their bayonets with such lethal effect that the enemy fled in wild disorder. During this fierce onslaught Capt. Millett was wounded by grenade fragments but refused evacuation until the objective was taken and firmly secured. The superb leadership, conspicuous courage, and consummate devotion to duty demonstrated by Capt. photos upon request, wood is good condition with 2 hairline cracks on either side of magazine well (as is common with the thinner wood after magazine conversion in 1878) i have fired around 200 rounds through this rifle and the cracks have not furthered in any way. the most noteworthy stock flaw is a pinky finger sized depression (grain appears not broken, it could be raised) near one of the cracks.
